WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:04.840
Hi everyone, welcome to this week's episode of the Grand Prixquel Pod.

00:04.840 --> 00:12.140
This week we saw the conclusion of three championships: Formula Winter Series, EC3 and EC4 Winter,

00:12.140 --> 00:15.840
as well as F1 Academy, kicking off in Shanghai.

00:15.840 --> 00:20.520
Our hosts this week are myself, Peter, Alex and Thia.

00:20.520 --> 00:27.120
So let's dive right into it.

00:27.120 --> 00:29.560
The Formula Winter Series concluded this week.

00:29.560 --> 00:38.820
After five rounds, we had our champion, Dries Van Langendonck, who, I mean, he was just crazy impressive and extremely dominant.

00:38.820 --> 00:44.340
And he won 9 out of 15 races, 12 podiums, 9 poles.

00:44.340 --> 00:48.380
It was like he'd always find a way for himself to be up front.

00:48.380 --> 00:56.500
And I think, for myself, what really impressed me about him was just his amazing racecraft and how smart he was.

00:56.500 --> 01:03.500
For example, at Aragon, he was holding back on the final lap as the front two are fighting, no point to go attack them.

01:03.500 --> 01:06.360
And then he saw a gap and just went for it and took the lead.

01:06.360 --> 01:12.090
And then here's another instance at Portimao where he stalled at the start.

01:12.090 --> 01:16.450
But then in about three racing laps, he went from P24 to P7.

01:16.450 --> 01:21.160
And without the safety cars, I think he could have honestly have won that race.

01:21.160 --> 01:33.120
And recently at Barcelona, he triple grand slammed, won every race, took a pole, led every lap and fastest lap and pretty much won the team's championship for Rodin.

01:33.360 --> 01:44.180
I think it's always crazy to have a driver that's like so incredibly dominant because I don't even think the grid was, it was like not the craziest kind of grid that you'd see in Italian F4 or something.

01:44.180 --> 01:50.700
But it was a very, very solid grid with quite a few drivers that I'd say had a good shot at like, going somewhere.

01:51.360 --> 01:57.700
And, you know, I'm kind of biased in favour of Ary Bansal, but I think he did really, really well considering everything.

01:57.700 --> 02:00.340
But Dries was just on that other level.

02:00.340 --> 02:14.260
And I'm pretty sure that what he mentioned somewhere before and kind of also texted, that he's probably going to follow that Antonelli/Slater route of just winning everything in his path, you know.

02:14.260 --> 02:16.340
I think it'll be really interesting to watch him.

02:16.860 --> 02:27.340
Yeah, and as you mentioned Bansal, I mean, he's no slouch. He's last year's GB4 champion and he just had some horrific luck as well, which also made things harder for him.

02:27.340 --> 02:36.520
For example, in the final two weekends, he stalled and got hit recently. He got taken out by another driver the previous week.

02:36.520 --> 02:38.260
So he's just a bit of bad luck.

02:38.260 --> 02:46.240
And even Thomas Bearman had consistent pace. He really showed up in the last two rounds taking podiums, challenging for wins.

02:46.800 --> 02:50.980
No race wins at all, which is. puts asterisk on it, in a way.

02:50.980 --> 02:59.480
But he still had consistent pace and just could be a bit messy at times, which very much kind of slowed his challenge, I feel like.

02:59.480 --> 03:06.960
Yeah, I mean, after, I think it was British F4 last season, I was not rating him as like the next big thing.

03:06.960 --> 03:10.560
So I think he spots pretty clearly beneath Dries.

03:10.560 --> 03:13.600
And, I mean, Ary, I really think he's a good driver.

03:13.600 --> 03:24.460
But GB4 is, in my opinion, not really that, you know, comparable to just easily make a step up and fight for such a championship with such more experienced throws.

03:24.520 --> 03:31.220
Because I do think that if you come from British F4, you have quite the bigger advantage than if you come from GB4.

03:31.220 --> 03:35.660
So I think against, let's say, normal guys, Ary Bansal did really good.

03:35.660 --> 03:39.300
And we have to keep in mind that Dries is also with McLaren.

03:39.300 --> 03:43.740
He probably gets loads of support there, which other drivers do not have.

03:43.740 --> 03:48.020
He's done a lot of testing as well, which always helps, but the raw pace is there.

03:48.020 --> 03:54.120
To expand on Bansal, he is doing Italian F4 this year, so that will be very interesting to see.

03:54.120 --> 04:02.000
So is Bearman as well, Italian F4 with VAR, following in the steps of brother Ollie doing it with VAR.

04:02.000 --> 04:08.280
Other than that, I mean, what do we think of Dries’ teammates, Ethan Lennon and Alfie Slater?

04:08.280 --> 04:11.740
I feel like Lennon surprised me quite a bit in the wet.

04:11.740 --> 04:14.520
I was not expecting this performance from him.

04:14.520 --> 04:16.700
And I think he was a bit unknown.

04:16.700 --> 04:21.270
He did do Ginetta Juniors last year, but he wasn't very known going into the series.

04:21.270 --> 04:23.080
And he was quite solid.

04:23.080 --> 04:29.720
Of course, very behind teammate Dries, but him and Alfie Slater were at a quite similar level.

04:29.720 --> 04:34.320
I mean, so much so that they crashed into each other in race two at Barcelona.

04:34.320 --> 04:40.420
I mean, Thomas and Alfie just really had that battle of the younger brothers going on to me.

04:40.420 --> 04:42.700
So I think it was really funny to see them both.

04:42.700 --> 04:56.360
And I think both of them should be able to, you know, take advantage of the fact that they come from a racing family who knows how to, you know, prepare, how to go into such a season with, you know, preparation.

04:56.360 --> 04:57.450
What do you need for it?

04:57.450 --> 05:00.320
Like, they probably also get like, a few tips from their brothers.

05:00.560 --> 05:03.450
And both their brothers are incredibly good.

05:03.450 --> 05:06.540
I mean, Ollie Bearman is P5 in F1 right now.

05:06.540 --> 05:09.560
And we all know how good Freddie Slater is.

05:09.560 --> 05:16.980
I mean, they're kind of nepo babies because, like, if you have the name Bearman on your car, obviously people are going to, like, expect a few more things from you.

05:17.220 --> 05:17.890
Oh, yeah, definitely.

05:17.890 --> 05:22.640
And, yeah, Slater was kind of, you know, the weakest of the three Rodins, I would say.

05:22.640 --> 05:24.380
He's almost behind the other two.

05:24.380 --> 05:26.770
I mean, he had a big gap between Dries and the other two.

05:26.770 --> 05:29.080
But then Lennon was ahead of Slater.

05:29.080 --> 05:31.500
So it sets up British F4;

05:31.500 --> 05:34.600
I mean, we have both of them doing British F4 this year.

05:34.600 --> 05:37.800
So it's very much a thing we're going to have to see.

05:37.800 --> 05:40.620
And I feel like I very much enjoyed the series overall.

05:40.620 --> 05:44.280
It was extremely fun racing, especially Aragon.

05:44.280 --> 05:45.420
What a track.

05:45.420 --> 05:48.140
I mean, we had consistent battles for the lead.

05:48.140 --> 05:50.320
It was extremely enjoyable to watch.

05:50.320 --> 05:56.680
If you haven't watched it, I thoroughly recommend you go find the race and rewatch it because they are just so much fun.

05:56.680 --> 06:01.040
So I feel like we need to give a shout out to the female drivers in the series.

06:01.040 --> 06:02.160
We had quite a few.

06:02.160 --> 06:05.440
I was particularly impressed by Chiara Bättig.

06:05.440 --> 06:12.220
Even though she came second in that, she podiumed, that race does have a bit of an asterisk due to the weather chaos.

06:12.220 --> 06:16.580
What really impressed me about her was the fact she was fighting for points.

06:16.580 --> 06:20.420
She was very close to scoring quite a few points, especially at Aragon.

06:20.420 --> 06:24.760
She was right up there with the male drivers, fighting with them.

06:24.760 --> 06:27.260
And it was really impressive to me to see her race craft.

06:27.260 --> 06:28.920
She finished P10.

06:28.920 --> 06:32.580
She came a bit on the unlucky end of things.

06:32.580 --> 06:34.400
But overall, she was very impressive.

06:34.400 --> 06:36.380
Finished P17 in the end.

06:36.380 --> 06:38.360
And I'm excited for her,

06:38.360 --> 06:41.040
I believe British F4 campaign this year.

06:41.040 --> 06:48.740
I thought we had, obviously, quite a few female drivers, which I think is, once again, really nice to see them, you know, do their first things.

06:48.740 --> 06:57.400
I think it's always kind of sad to see them only do a handful of rounds because it's really difficult to join in when you're joining in like round three.

06:57.540 --> 07:07.820
And everyone else has more experience, as we've seen with Caitlyn McDaniel, who seemed to not, you know, have as much of an easy time as drivers who may be the whole season and the preseason testings and stuff.

07:07.820 --> 07:20.520
But I still want to point out that I was really hopeful for Zoe Florescu, who, in my opinion, I mean, she finished around like the 20 area, which is, in my opinion, for her debut in single seaters,

07:20.520 --> 07:22.180
i's really not bad.

07:22.180 --> 07:27.820
And I look into standings and I just think really interesting how many women we have.

07:27.820 --> 07:41.540
And, you know, I wish we would have seen more do full season like Chiara Bättig and Ginevra Panzeri, because I think that if we had seen that, we would have also seen more of them make proper like step up in the series itself.

07:41.540 --> 07:51.120
As we've seen with, I feel like, Chiara Bättig, who's like last round was a lot better than her first round, because you improve with more time on the track, you know?

07:51.120 --> 07:51.820
Yeah, definitely.

07:51.820 --> 07:56.360
And like one final draw we've not talked about, who I want to mention, is Rocco Coronel.

07:56.360 --> 08:02.600
He was the one, in the first weekend especially, he was the one who was able to run the closest to Dries.

08:02.600 --> 08:08.140
He only contested the first three rounds, but he had brilliant race craft.

08:08.140 --> 08:12.100
He would have a great defense work, work his way up through the field.

08:12.100 --> 08:19.340
His main weak point was qualifying, but his wise was able to, he even took a win over Dries in the wet,

08:19.440 --> 08:21.060
which was extremely impressive.

08:21.060 --> 08:28.180
One last driver that I want to point out for me is Arjen Kräling, the German driver, who I'm obviously a bit biased for,

08:28.180 --> 08:32.240
because I saw him give his debut in British F4 last season.

08:32.240 --> 08:35.170
And since then, it's obviously been on my mind to support him.

08:35.170 --> 08:45.160
I think he really, I think if you look at standings, it's too funny how much of a step up he made, because when he won his first race in, where was it?

08:45.160 --> 08:46.280
In Ricardo Tormo.

08:46.860 --> 08:53.500
After that, the next race, he didn't score points, but after that, he just scored points, five races after each other.

08:53.500 --> 08:59.900
And it's like, really good run actually, which I think is really interesting, because it just looks like that win really took, you know,

08:59.900 --> 09:03.410
kind of, maybe took pressure off his shoulders, or maybe it did more pressure.

09:03.550 --> 09:10.900
But it helped him, because it really looks funny, because before his win, he only scored points in the very first race, where he finished P6.

09:10.900 --> 09:14.740
And he didn't score any points for seven races, I think.

09:14.940 --> 09:23.160
And then he just, after, you know, one other, when he didn't finish, he just finished P7, P4, P7, P8, P5, which is really solid, I think.

09:23.160 --> 09:31.700
So, of course, we had Rocco Coronel leaving Formula Winter Series to go compete in the Spanish F4 / EC4 Winter Series,

09:31.700 --> 09:35.290
which, again, another brilliant F4 series.

09:35.290 --> 09:39.900
And, like, the title was being decided in the most crazy way possible.

09:40.040 --> 09:47.660
It is the most kind of F4 thing to ever happen, with it being based on penalties, 30-second penalties, to be more specific.

09:47.660 --> 09:50.000
I love Formula 4 Series.

09:50.000 --> 09:59.540
It was quite a short series, with only three rounds, nine races, but it was an extremely enjoyable series to watch.

09:59.540 --> 10:08.900
I feel like the racing was extremely fun to watch, and we had our champion, Noah Monterio, who had improved a lot from last season,

10:08.900 --> 10:15.000
having been P9 in this championship last year and P8 in Spanish F4 last year.

10:15.000 --> 10:21.380
So, we're very much setting himself up as a potential title challenger in Spanish F4 later this year.

10:21.380 --> 10:26.900
We're looking at a really solid grid, and it's, again, I'm very excited for the main series,

10:26.900 --> 10:30.200
because, as you said, it was a very short season.

10:30.200 --> 10:34.980
And, sadly, that means that we can't see everyone, kind of, you know, make the grounds.

10:34.980 --> 10:38.500
And one bad weekend means the whole thing is basically ruined.

10:38.500 --> 10:40.980
And, obviously, I'm looking at the female drivers again.

10:40.980 --> 10:42.600
Luna Fluxa, is it?

10:42.600 --> 10:44.000
Do you pronounce it like that?

10:44.000 --> 10:45.100
I think so.

10:45.100 --> 10:45.790
You do.

10:45.790 --> 10:51.360
In any way, she got podium in the second race, which was really solid, scored some more points.

10:51.700 --> 10:56.380
I felt like the second track really did not really work out for her.

10:56.380 --> 10:58.660
Like, it seems really difficult for her.

10:58.660 --> 11:05.460
And the problem is, if you only have three race weekends, and you don't really get into the mindset on one of them,

11:05.460 --> 11:07.800
I mean, the whole season is kind of thrown away.

11:07.800 --> 11:13.340
Yeah, and for her, this is her first ever F4 championship and race she's ever done.

11:13.340 --> 11:17.920
It's a massive learning curve, and she did improve a bit in Aragon.

11:17.920 --> 11:24.420
She scored points in all three races in the final round, so it is maybe setting up something more in the main series,

11:24.420 --> 11:29.060
because she has proven she does have the pace, which is just now keeping it consistent.

11:29.480 --> 11:35.740
Yeah, I mean, if she goes back to Jarama, and, you know, she does it again, and she gets that experience,

11:35.740 --> 11:41.260
I think even then, she'd be able to, you know, go for points and stuff there, but sadly not in this challenge.

11:41.260 --> 11:43.300
But overall, really solid season.

11:43.300 --> 11:47.980
As for other female drivers, we had Maria Germano Neto.

11:47.980 --> 11:53.840
I thought it was quite interesting, because I haven't really heard of her before this season,

11:53.840 --> 11:57.340
but I talked to people and a lot of what I've heard was like,

11:57.480 --> 12:04.000
“she has great race craft”, and I think we saw that when, in one race, she went from like P20 or something to P11.

12:04.000 --> 12:12.900
