21:05.330 --> 21:07.560
Alex has not driven any of these circuits.

21:07.560 --> 21:10.940
He's not driven Poitimao, he's not driven Jarama, he's not driven Aragon.

21:10.940 --> 21:14.580
So, I'd say this is a pretty decent season performance.

21:14.580 --> 21:18.800
And obviously, you know, both Strauven and Heuzenroeder had a bit of bad luck.

21:18.800 --> 21:25.800
And, you know, in a three-race, three-round championship, like, one weekend of bad luck really, really affects you.

21:25.800 --> 21:30.220
Um, so, I think this has been pretty positive.

21:30.580 --> 21:38.880
I think I'm looking forward to the main campaign because when it comes to the main Eurocup 3 season, Alex does actually have experience on these tracks.

21:38.880 --> 21:43.740
He's raced Paul Ricard before he's raced Monza, he's raced Imola, he's raced Barcelona.

21:43.740 --> 21:47.610
And Poitimao is coming, like, they're racing at Poitimao again.

21:47.610 --> 21:50.940
Uh, I think, obviously, no one's raced the Madring yet.

21:50.940 --> 21:53.980
And we don't even know if they're going to race the Madring yet.

21:53.980 --> 21:57.760
Uh, Silverstone and the Hungaroring should be interesting as well.

21:58.120 --> 22:09.220
Um, a little bit of math that I did, and my math might be wronged, but had Alex not lost out on the win in Jarama due to that five-second penalty, he would have finished the championship in P2.

22:09.220 --> 22:13.560
Because, um, he finished the race after the penalty in P6.

22:13.560 --> 22:15.080
So, he scored eight points.

22:15.080 --> 22:16.820
And, obviously, it's 25 points for a win.

22:16.980 --> 22:21.060
So, that means he lost out on 17 points by losing out on that win.

22:21.060 --> 22:26.160
And, if he adds 17 points onto his, like, end of season total, he ends up with 91 points.

22:26.160 --> 22:28.360
And, Egozi finished the season on 92.

22:28.360 --> 22:33.160
However, Egozi, he inherited the win from Alex when Alex got penalized.

22:33.160 --> 22:41.720
So, if Alex didn't get penalized, and, obviously, Egozi wouldn't have inherited the win, so he would have had less than 92 points.

22:41.720 --> 22:44.480
Which would put Alex in P2 in the championship.

22:44.740 --> 22:47.480
Which kind of sucks, but we live and we learn.

22:47.480 --> 22:50.260
And, obviously, we'll improve for the main campaign.

22:50.260 --> 22:56.080
And, yeah, we finished runner-up in the rookie championship behind René Lammers.

22:56.080 --> 22:58.000
I think we were eight points behind him.

22:58.000 --> 23:01.200
But, yeah, overall, it's been a pretty consistent season.

23:01.200 --> 23:05.400
And, I'm looking forward to the main Eurocup 3 campaign.

23:05.400 --> 23:07.260
Thank you.

23:07.260 --> 23:11.040
We can go back to everyone else now.

23:11.040 --> 23:13.080
So, we had other drivers.

23:13.360 --> 23:17.640
We had James Egozi as well, who finished.

23:17.640 --> 23:19.920
He had, he was a title challenger.

23:19.920 --> 23:24.180
And, he had more wins than Al-Azhari with his double amount of wins.

23:24.180 --> 23:26.640
But, he had two retirements.

23:26.640 --> 23:27.380
A DNS.

23:27.380 --> 23:32.320
He ended up 53 points behind, which really points to Keanu's consistency.

23:32.980 --> 23:37.300
But, despite all of this, he still managed to stay runner-up in the championship.

23:37.300 --> 23:44.440
And, we also had Thomas Strauven, who, I mean, everyone, I think, going into the season, he was very much a title-favorite.

23:44.440 --> 23:49.240
But, again, it's just, especially when the championship is so short, with only nine races.

23:49.240 --> 23:54.680
One bad weekend, and that throws away your entire series- season, I mean.

23:54.920 --> 23:58.480
Because, he was extremely dominant last year in Spanish F4.

23:58.480 --> 24:05.180
But, when it comes to the main campaign, the likes of Strauven is certainly going to be up there.

24:05.180 --> 24:07.040
Also, Alex Powell, I think.

24:07.040 --> 24:14.220
I think, as with Strauven, I think he should have, kind of, an advantage when we talk about the tracks and the circuits.

24:14.220 --> 24:18.520
Because, you know, it did not necessarily help him here, but we only did three circuits.

24:18.520 --> 24:25.220
But, overall, I think he should have an advantage over those drivers that, you know, do not know these circuits.

24:25.220 --> 24:29.100
That do not have this experience in Spanish racing.

24:29.100 --> 24:36.200
Because, what I feel like is that the series that really are located in Spain, they are kind of similar to each other.

24:36.200 --> 24:39.960
And, if you have the experience, the vibes, you get into there.

24:39.960 --> 24:41.160
You know what to do.

24:41.160 --> 24:42.780
You know, I think it really helps.

24:42.780 --> 24:49.260
I think, overall, Powell should be someone who has, you know, more experience going maybe wheel to wheel.

24:49.260 --> 24:51.100
You know, he did two seasons of F4.

24:51.100 --> 24:54.020
You know, he did the Formula Regional Middle East Championship. 

24:54.020 --> 24:57.440
He's someone who has a lot of experience with who I think should do it.

24:57.440 --> 25:00.820
But, Strauven, we got that advantage of experience over him.

25:00.820 --> 25:05.480
Speaking of experience, I feel like Kasper Sztuka was a bit underwhelming.

25:05.480 --> 25:09.800
Given how much more experience he has compared to everyone else.

25:09.800 --> 25:14.860
I mean, he didn't really have any notable races I can think of or any notable finishes.

25:14.860 --> 25:20.220
And, of course, he is an Italian F4 champion, albeit from 2023.

25:20.220 --> 25:23.360
Wasn't Kasper Sztuka in F3 at some point?

25:23.360 --> 25:24.380
Or am I making s*** up?

25:24.380 --> 25:26.300
No, he did F3 as well.

25:26.660 --> 25:30.040
Yeah, like, I think he should have experience, but…

25:30.040 --> 25:31.880
Maybe it's because of the team he was with.

25:31.880 --> 25:34.460
Not exactly the best team, but…

25:34.460 --> 25:39.040
Again, it's very much what you would expect from someone with his experience.

25:39.040 --> 25:41.420
He didn't have a single points finish.

25:41.420 --> 25:41.940
Oh.

25:41.940 --> 25:45.700
Maybe partly down to the team, but with someone who's been in F3 as well.

25:45.700 --> 25:47.820
You do expect more.

25:47.980 --> 25:57.020
And we also had René Lammers, who, again, like Rocco Coronel in the EC4 winter, was all or nothing with podiums.

25:57.020 --> 26:01.120
Basically, podiums, a P4, and then no points finishers.

26:01.120 --> 26:02.940
Which, you know, maybe a confident experience.

26:03.220 --> 26:06.220
But despite this, he did win the rookie championship, but…

26:06.220 --> 26:14.640
So, again, it's probably just an experience thing, which, as you've said before, these winter championships are a great way just to get more experience.

26:14.640 --> 26:19.980
I think we should go on to F1 Academy, which I was very, very excited about.

26:19.980 --> 26:23.200
All my comments, all the comments that we have made, are from me.

26:23.320 --> 26:31.900
And I went through all the races to have exact data on every single driver and to figure out exactly what happened to every single driver.

26:31.900 --> 26:36.400
Just in case no one saw the overcase that Ava Dobson did.

26:36.400 --> 26:38.880
I think it's very important to talk about this.

26:38.880 --> 26:47.400
So, I felt that, like, Natalia Granada, she was great on debut, especially for somebody who had only done sports cars and endurance.

26:47.400 --> 26:51.060
And getting a podium in race one was great.

26:51.060 --> 26:56.820
And it was just unfortunate that she had that collision in race two.

26:56.820 --> 26:59.380
Yeah, I think it was kind of a rookie mistake.

26:59.380 --> 27:01.780
I watched the scene again and again.

27:01.780 --> 27:04.620
And it was difficult because she should have braked.

27:04.620 --> 27:08.700
But it was probably just ended with someone going, driving into her back.

27:08.700 --> 27:10.580
Because she was in a kind of difficult situation.

27:10.580 --> 27:12.820
Like, she was already on the outside.

27:12.820 --> 27:15.700
In front of her, there's, I think it was Ferreira.

27:15.700 --> 27:17.740
On the side of her, there was someone else.

27:17.740 --> 27:20.200
And she just kind of went into Ferreira.

27:20.200 --> 27:21.680
And it was a bit unfortunate.

27:21.680 --> 27:27.580
But honestly, it's just something, I think, that can happen in your second ever Formula 4 race.

27:27.580 --> 27:29.960
Yeah, I mean, she very much did in the sprint.

27:29.960 --> 27:32.640
And qualifying P7 on debut is impressive.

27:32.640 --> 27:35.780
And then, you know, she held it off the line and just stayed consistent.

27:36.240 --> 27:37.460
In the sprint race especially.

27:37.460 --> 27:39.420
So that's really all one can do.

27:39.420 --> 27:42.800
And it had to do with the safety car, restarting still was still solid.

27:42.800 --> 27:46.360
I think it was really strong of her to keep so close to Gademan.

27:46.360 --> 27:51.540
Who, with all due respect, should, you know, have driven away from her with years more of that F4 experience.

27:51.540 --> 27:53.740
And in her second F1 Academy year.

27:53.740 --> 27:57.800
And even Felbermayr, who had an absolutely great weekend overall, I think.

27:57.800 --> 28:00.680
And who managed to overtake the people behind her.

28:00.680 --> 28:02.540
Did not quite manage to get her.

28:02.540 --> 28:06.420
Which I think just shows that her speed, especially in the sprint, was really good.

28:06.420 --> 28:09.480
Especially after everyone did not expect her to do well.

28:09.640 --> 28:12.580
I think I briefly want to mention Alba Larson.

28:12.580 --> 28:14.300
Because she had a great qualifying.

28:14.300 --> 28:17.780
But then, the races did not go her way at all.

28:17.780 --> 28:21.280
And I feel like she's still making these rookie mistakes.

28:21.280 --> 28:24.460
Which you really shouldn’t be making going into her second season.

28:24.460 --> 28:25.960
And we know she's fast.

28:25.960 --> 28:28.220
But ultimately, she's in her second season.

28:28.220 --> 28:32.380
And with the F1 Academy calendar being so short.

28:32.380 --> 28:34.420
And having so few races, as it does.

28:34.420 --> 28:38.720
Because we now know that, unfortunately, due to the conflict in the Middle East.

28:38.840 --> 28:40.740
Where we hope everyone is staying safe.

28:40.740 --> 28:43.120
The Saturday round has officially been cancelled.

28:43.120 --> 28:45.480
So, we're only down to 12 races.

28:45.480 --> 28:49.500
So, having a poor weekend is ever so costly.

28:49.500 --> 28:51.520
If you want to challenge for the title.

28:51.520 --> 28:56.180
And for Larson, I mean, she got front wing damage in the sprint race.

28:56.180 --> 28:59.480
And then, I mean, what do we think of that safety car?

28:59.480 --> 29:01.960
If we start mistaking the second race.

29:01.960 --> 29:04.740
I think it was just something that should not have happened.

29:04.740 --> 29:07.720
