29:08.040 --> 29:11.980
She struggled with, you know, restarting on the safety car.

29:11.980 --> 29:20.820
And I think her whole thing is just like, I wasn't sure if the problem that she had there was that she, you know, thought that she was doing it good.

29:20.820 --> 29:22.920
And, you know, made a small mistake.

29:22.920 --> 29:29.500
Or if the problem was that she had this huge, huge, you know, weight on her shoulders.

29:29.500 --> 29:31.180
Because she's now backed by Ferrari.

29:31.180 --> 29:32.660
And people are looking at her.

29:32.660 --> 29:36.300
She's like, surprisingly enough, she's the title favorite for a lot of people.

29:36.760 --> 29:43.340
Even though, with all due respect, after last season, it did not, you know, she was not the highest rookie.

29:43.340 --> 29:45.460
She's not the highest of the returning rookies.

29:45.460 --> 29:50.480
And she's, I'm sorry, but I think, I think she can be in the title fight.

29:50.600 --> 29:58.800
But I think the title fight is more between other drivers who have more experience, who have more wins than podiums already.

29:59.020 --> 30:02.380
And so I think it's quite interesting, the huge weight on her shoulders.

30:02.380 --> 30:06.140
And I think it could have negatively impacted her.

30:06.140 --> 30:09.600
Because it just seemed to me that she was trying to go fast.

30:09.600 --> 30:12.240
Because maybe she was afraid of, you know, losing that win.

30:12.240 --> 30:14.160
Because it's always s*** to lose a win.

30:14.160 --> 30:19.880
And you don't want it to happen, especially if you have Felbermayer and Palmowski behind you.

30:19.880 --> 30:26.800
Yeah, and speaking of Palmowski, I mean, she's incredibly dominant in qualifying winning pole by four tenths.

30:26.800 --> 30:33.860
And in the sprint, the main thing is, I feel like, when you want to be a title challenger, is just to stay out of trouble.

30:33.860 --> 30:37.080
Which Larson did not do, but Palmowski did.

30:37.080 --> 30:41.160
And she brought it home in P5 in the end.

30:41.160 --> 30:45.080
But it's just more about just inheriting positions and keeping it clean.

30:45.080 --> 30:46.300
That is the main.

30:46.300 --> 30:49.560
And we saw overtaking was quite hard.

30:49.560 --> 30:56.580
Yeah, I saw someone point out and call it that from what we saw from Palmowski was that quiet confidence,

30:56.580 --> 31:02.460
especially when she overtook, I think it was Lisa Billard who fell kind of back at some point.

31:02.460 --> 31:04.620
And who she pretty easily overtook.

31:04.620 --> 31:09.880
And the commentators in Germany called her kind of, you know, a bit radical, a bit aggressive.

31:09.880 --> 31:11.860
But she stayed out of trouble.

31:11.860 --> 31:19.000
And she did great because she inherited positions from what Alba Larson pretty much threw away in both races.

31:19.360 --> 31:21.400
So I think it was really solid of her.

31:21.400 --> 31:28.720
I think we need to admit that the start in the feature race just did not, you know, work out perfectly for her.

31:28.960 --> 31:32.440
But she still kept it up pretty strong after that.

31:32.440 --> 31:34.500
Should have, could have maybe done more.

31:34.500 --> 31:41.540
But what I would point out mainly is Emma Felbermayr, who, in my opinion, was by far the strongest driver this weekend.

31:41.540 --> 31:43.720
